{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540109"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16738"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16738"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.11,0.05,0.58,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89977"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9429"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74136"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2186"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"8985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43653"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89977"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with fever, dry cough, and shortness of breath that developed six hours after his shift at a sugar cane processing plant. He has worked at the plant for three months. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 102/min, blood pressure 128/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Fine crackles are heard throughout both lung fields. His chest X-ray shows diffuse interstitial infiltrates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchial asthma","Melioidosis","Bacterial pneumonia","Bagassosis","Farmer\u0027s lung"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of bagassosis, an occupational hypersensitivity pneumonitis caused by exposure to thermophilic actinomycetes that grow in stored, mouldy sugar cane fibres (bagasse). The timing of symptom onset (4-8 hours after exposure) and the combination of fever, dyspnoea, and cough are characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBagassosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects workers in sugar cane processing facilities who handle bagasse, particularly if proper ventilation and protective equipment are not used. The diagnosis is primarily clinical, based on the history of exposure and typical symptoms. Chest X-ray typically shows diffuse interstitial infiltrates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with productive cough, focal consolidation on chest X-ray, and does not have the clear temporal relationship with workplace exposure seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchial asthma\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with wheeze rather than crackles, and while it can be occupationally induced, it would not typically present with fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFarmer\u0027s lung\u003C/strong\u003E is also a hypersensitivity pneumonitis but is specifically associated with exposure to mouldy hay rather than sugar cane fibres. The clinical presentation would be similar but the exposure history is different.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelioidosis\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E, can occur in sugar cane workers but typically presents as a more severe systemic illness with pneumonia and/or abscess formation. It is also more common in tropical regions and in patients with underlying conditions like diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bagassosis is an occupational hypersensitivity pneumonitis caused by exposure to mouldy sugar cane fibres.","Acute symptoms typically develop 4-8 hours after exposure and include fever, cough, and dyspnoea.","Prevention through proper ventilation and personal protective equipment is essential in sugar cane processing."],"references":["Rinaldi MG, Doherty M, Peden D. Bagassosis. Occup Med (Lond). 1987;37(2):67-72. doi:10.1093/occmed/37.2.67","Wild LG, Lopez M. Hypersensitivity pneumonitis: a comprehensive review. J Investig Allergol Clin Immunol. 2001;11(1):3-15.","Alif SM, Glass DC, Abramson M, Hoy R, Sim MR Occupational Lung Diseases in Australia. 2020 Feb. Pages 1-86. Safe Work Australia [cited 2025 Mar 11] Available at: https://www.safeworkaustralia.gov.au/sites/default/files/2020-08/Occupational%20lung%20diseases%20in%20Australia%202006-2019.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74136"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16738"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74136"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T14:58:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T14:58:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item"